Although physical fitness is a key indicator of health status, the economic implications of comprehensive fitness profiles—encompassing both health-related and skill-based components—remain poorly understood. This study examined the association between comprehensive physical fitness tiers and annual healthcare expenditures by linking the National Fitness Award 100 (NFA100) and National Health Insurance Service (NHIS)
databases, with the aim of providing empirical evidence to inform cost-effective public health policies

Fitness tiers were classified using age- and sex-standardized performance across health-related and skill-based components, with the “participation-only” group comprising individuals who completed assessments but did not meet minimum performance thresholds.

Among older adults, higher levels of skill-based fitness, including agility and functional mobility, were consistently associated with lower healthcare expenditures.

Higher levels of comprehensive physical fitness were robustly associated with lower healthcare expenditures. These findings suggest that skill-based fitness may serve as an important indicator of medical utilization in older populations and underscore the potential role of the National Fitness Award 100 as a population-level surveillance and prevention tool contributing to fiscal sustainability in rapidly aging societies

We conducted a retrospective cohort analysis using linked data from the National Fitness Award 100 (NFA100) and the National Health Insurance Service (NHIS) database from 2015 to 2022. The NFA100 is a government-led program that systematically assesses health-related and skill-related fitness components using standardized protocols. The NHIS database is a nationwide administrative repository that captures healthcare utilization and reimbursed expenditures for nearly the entire population of the Republic of Korea. Linking these large-scale datasets enabled a comprehensive examination of the association between objectively measured fitness levels and subsequent healthcare expenditures, minimizing biases related to self-reported measures and incomplete medical records.

Association between Physical Fitness Tiers and Annual Healthcare Costs (USD Adjusted)
The association between physical fitness tiers and annual healthcare costs, stratified by age group and sex, is presented in Table 5. Overall, a significant

In the adult population, the 'Participation-only' group incurred significantly higher costs compared to Tier 1. For adult males, the additional annual expenditure was 112,853 KRW (approx. 87.35 USD) (95% CI: 45.47 to 128.26 USD). Similarly, adult females in the lowest fitness category spent an additional 111,514 KRW (approx. 86.31 USD) (95% CI: 42.42 to 130.21 USD).

The economic impact was substantially larger in the senior group. Senior males in the 'Participation-only' category incurred an additional 573,830 KRW (approx. 444.16 USD) (95% CI: 360.82 to 527.49 USD) per year compared to those in Tier 1. For senior females, the additional cost was 552,870 KRW (approx. 427.93 USD) (95% CI: 357.16 to 498.72 USD). Notably, even reaching Tier 3 was associated with a cost reduction of nearly 220,000 KRW (~170 USD) compared to the Participation-only group, highlighting the significant economic value of maintaining at least a basic level of physical fitness in older age.

In the senior group, the substantial expenditure disparity observed in functional mobility assessments—specifically the 3-m up-and-go and Figure 8 walk—is particularly noteworthy. These results align with the

, which posits that when an individual’s physical capacity falls below a critical level, the risk of catastrophic health events and subsequent medical utilization increases disproportionately. The fact that seniors in the 'Participation-only' group incurred over $400 more in annual expenditures than those in Tier 1 underscores that
impaired mobility is not merely a clinical concern but a primary driver of geriatric healthcare expenditures.

The economic significance of these markers can be largely explained by their direct link to fall-related injuries, which represent some of the most costly medical events for the elderly, frequently necessitating emergency interventions and long-term rehabilitation. In this context, agility and balance serve as a primary

that preempts these high-cost incidents. This aligns with findings by Sherrington et al. (2019), who emphasized that balance-focused exercise is superior to resistance training alone in reducing both falls and subsequent medical expenditures.

Notably, while Caspersen et al. (1985) originally distinguished skill-related components as being primarily essential for athletic performance, our findings provide a critical extension to this paradigm. We demonstrate that these components are not merely for athletic excellence, but have profound implications for geriatric public health and the long-term economic sustainability of national healthcare systems.

A major strength of this study

is the large-scale integration of objective fitness measurements from the NFA100 with national administrative claims data from the NHIS, encompassing over 150,000 participants. This nationwide linkage minimizes recall bias inherent in self-reported data and provides a robust estimate of the "real-world" economic impact of physical

fitness. From a policy perspective, our findings indicate that national health strategies should prioritize transitioning sedentary or low-fitness individuals into at least the basic fitness tiers (Tier 3).
